      deepDiveTopics: [
        { topic: 'Block-Level Sync Engine', diagramSrc: '/diagrams/dropbox/deep-dive-block-sync.svg', detail: `The sync engine is the heart of Dropbox. When a file changes, the client splits it into 4MB blocks, computes SHA-256 hashes for each block, and sends the hash list to the server. The server compares against its block index and returns which hashes are missing. The client uploads only the missing blocks — meaning a small edit to a large file transfers just one 4MB block instead of the entire file. On the receiving end, other devices get a notification of the change, fetch the new metadata (updated block hash list), identify which blocks they already have locally, and download only the missing ones. This bidirectional delta sync is what makes Dropbox feel instant even for large files.` },
        { topic: 'Content-Addressed Deduplication', diagramSrc: '/diagrams/dropbox/deep-dive-dedup.svg', detail: `Every block in Dropbox's storage system is identified by its SHA-256 hash — the same content always produces the same hash. This means identical blocks across all users worldwide are stored exactly once. When a million users upload the same Windows installer, Dropbox stores it once and creates a million metadata references. Cross-user dedup savings typically reach 40-60% for enterprise accounts. The system uses a global block index (a massive key-value store mapping hash → storage location) to check existence. Security concern: hash probing attacks where an attacker sends hashes to check if specific files exist. Mitigation includes authentication requirements and rate limiting.` },
        { topic: 'Conflict Resolution Strategy', diagramSrc: '/diagrams/dropbox/deep-dive-conflict.svg', detail: `Conflicts occur when the same file is edited on two devices while offline. Dropbox uses optimistic concurrency with conflict copies. Each file has a version number that increments on every change. When a device syncs, it sends its expected version. If the server version is higher than expected, a conflict has occurred. Rather than silently overwriting (last-writer-wins), Dropbox creates a conflict copy named 'filename (conflicted copy date)'. For real-time collaboration on documents (like Google Docs), Operational Transform or CRDTs can merge concurrent character-level edits without creating copies. The choice depends on whether the system prioritizes simplicity (conflict copies) or seamlessness (OT/CRDT).` },
        { topic: 'Notification and Long Polling', diagramSrc: '/diagrams/dropbox/deep-dive-notification.svg', detail: `When a file changes on one device, all other devices need to know immediately. Dropbox uses long polling: the client opens an HTTP connection to the notification service and the server holds it open for up to 90 seconds. If a change occurs during that window, the server responds immediately with a cursor update. The client then fetches the full change list from the metadata service using this cursor. If no changes occur within 90 seconds, the connection closes and the client reconnects. This approach gives near-instant sync while being firewall-friendly (unlike WebSocket which some corporate networks block). Each device maintains its own cursor position in the change stream.` },
      ],

